      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Braise the rabbit",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Fry the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{lardons}} of lardons",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " in a casserole until golden. Remove and set aside. Brown the rabbit pieces in the same fat. Remove and set aside. Soften the onion for 5 minutes. Add garlic, thyme, and bay. Return the rabbit and lardons. Pour over ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{white-wine-dry}} of white wine",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{stock-chicken}} of chicken stock",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Cover and braise over low heat or in a 160°C oven for 90 minutes until the meat pulls from the bones. Transfer the rabbit to a board, pick all the meat from the bones, and discard the bones. Return the meat to the braising liquid.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the sauce and fill the pie",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Stir in the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{double-cream}} of cream",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and simmer for 5 minutes to reduce the sauce. Season with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sea-salt-flakes}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{black-pepper}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Off the heat, stir in the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{dijon-mustard}} of Dijon mustard",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Cool completely and refrigerate until cold. Spoon into the pie dish. Lay the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{puff-pastry}} of puff pastry",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " over the top, press and trim the edges, score, cut a vent, and brush with beaten egg.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bake",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 200°C (180°C fan). Bake for 35-40 minutes until the pastry is deep golden and the filling is bubbling. Rest for 10 minutes before cutting.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "rows": [
            {
              "fix": "Continue braising in 20-minute increments. Wild rabbit can take up to 2 hours.",
              "cause": "Heat was too low, or the rabbit was older and needs longer",
              "symptom": "Meat is tough after 90 minutes of braising"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Braise with the lid on. If the sauce is thin when finished, reduce it by simmering uncovered for 10 minutes before adding cream.",
              "cause": "Lid was left off during braising, allowing too much evaporation",
              "symptom": "Sauce is very thin"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Work slowly and carefully when picking the meat. Run fingers through the shredded meat feeling for hard pieces.",
              "cause": "Rabbit has many small rib and vertebral bones that are easy to miss",
              "symptom": "Small bones in the finished pie"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Always add Dijon mustard off the heat; it loses its sharpness if cooked for more than a minute.",
              "cause": "Mustard was added while the sauce was still hot",
              "symptom": "Mustard taste is absent"
            }
          ]
        },
        "content": []
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Rabbit pie appears in almost every British period cookery book from Mrs Beeton onwards. Wild rabbit was a staple protein in the British countryside for centuries, and the pie was the most reliable way to make a whole rabbit feed four people. Today it sits on the menu of gastropubs and farmhouse restaurants as a seasonal special, usually with a note about it being local wild rabbit.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
